# RFC-0024

# Endpoint Manifest Specification (EMS)

Status: Draft

Version: 0.1

Depends on:

* RFC-0000 Core Object Model
* RFC-0015 Model Class Registry
* RFC-0020 Hypervisor Architecture
* RFC-0023 Bundle Specification

---

# 1. Purpose

The Endpoint Manifest defines a concrete executable AI service published by a Hypervisor.

Unlike Bundles, Endpoint Manifests are mutable.

Multiple Endpoint Manifests MAY reference the same Bundle.

An Endpoint Manifest represents the externally visible contract between a Hypervisor and the AiDN network.

---

# 2. Design Principles

### EMS-1

Bundles are immutable.

Endpoint Manifests are mutable.

---

### EMS-2

An Endpoint represents a service.

It does not represent a specific implementation.

---

### EMS-3

Implementation details remain private.

Only observable properties are published.

---

### EMS-4

Every Endpoint owns its own reputation.

Changing implementation affects trust but does not change Endpoint identity.

---

# 3. Endpoint Identity

Every Endpoint SHALL contain:

```yaml
endpoint:

  endpoint_id:

  owner_wallet:

  created_at:

  bundle_id:

  bundle_hash:

  configuration_hash:
```

`endpoint_id` remains stable throughout the lifetime of the Endpoint.

---

# 4. Model Declaration

Every public Endpoint SHALL declare its Model Class.

```yaml
identity:

  display_name: Opus4.6-class

  model_class: opus-class
```

`display_name` is controlled by the operator.

`model_class` SHALL reference an entry in the Model Class Registry.

---

# 5. Endpoint Profile

The operator MAY publish descriptive metadata.

```yaml
profile:

  summary:

  strengths:

  limitations:

  recommended_tasks:

  supported_languages:

  preferred_formats:

  examples:
```

The Profile is informational only.

---

# 6. Runtime Configuration

Runtime configuration defines Endpoint behavior.

```yaml
runtime:

  context_length:

  temperature:

  top_p:

  top_k:

  max_tokens:

  streaming:

  timeout:
```

Changing any runtime parameter SHALL generate a new Configuration Snapshot.

---

# 7. Publication Policy

Each Endpoint defines its publication policy.

```yaml
publication:

  visibility:

    public | private

  discoverable:

    true | false

  validation:

    enabled | disabled

  accepts_external_requests:

    true | false
```

Each property is independent.

---

# 8. Pricing

Every Endpoint SHALL publish pricing using Billing Units.

```yaml
pricing:

  billing_unit:

  input_price:

  output_price:

  fixed_price:
```

Supported Billing Units include:

* token
* second
* image
* page
* request
* custom

Examples:

LLM

```yaml
pricing:

  billing_unit: token

  input_price: 2.5

  output_price: 7.0
```

Speech-to-Text

```yaml
pricing:

  billing_unit: second

  input_price: 0.4

  output_price: 0
```

Image Generation

```yaml
pricing:

  billing_unit: image

  fixed_price: 4.5
```

The Hypervisor reports usage.

Wallet services compute settlements.

---

# 9. Validation Status

```yaml
validation:

  enabled:

  model_class_supported:

  verification_status:

  validation_profile:
```

Verification status SHALL be one of:

* unsupported
* pending
* active
* suspended

---

# 10. Configuration Snapshot

Every execution-relevant modification SHALL generate a new Configuration Snapshot.

Configuration Snapshot includes:

* BundleHash
* Runtime configuration
* Scheduler configuration
* Publication policy
* Provider-independent execution configuration

Each Snapshot SHALL produce a unique ConfigurationHash.

---

# 11. Reputation Continuity

Endpoint identity remains stable across Configuration Snapshot changes.

However,

every Configuration Snapshot change contributes to Reputation recalculation according to RFC-0009.

Large implementation changes SHALL temporarily reduce confidence until sufficient new observations have been collected.

---

# 12. Privacy

The Endpoint Manifest SHALL NOT expose:

* provider implementation;
* execution topology;
* local or remote execution;
* orchestration strategy;
* internal routing;
* provider chain.

Execution remains private to the Hypervisor.

---

# 13. Provider Independence

An Endpoint MAY change its Provider implementation without changing Endpoint identity.

Example:

```text
Endpoint

↓

Bundle

↓

Provider A

↓

Provider B
```

Such changes SHALL produce a new Configuration Snapshot.

---

# 14. Lifecycle

```mermaid
stateDiagram-v2

[*] --> Created

Created --> Published

Published --> Active

Active --> Updating

Updating --> Active

Active --> Suspended

Suspended --> Active

Active --> Removed

Removed --> [*]
```

---

# 15. Discovery Contract

Discovery APIs SHALL expose only:

* Endpoint Identity
* Model Class
* Capability
* Pricing
* Reputation
* Validation Status
* ConfigurationHash

No implementation details SHALL be published.

---

# 16. Design Invariants

Invariant 1

Endpoint identity is permanent.

---

Invariant 2

BundleHash is immutable.

---

Invariant 3

ConfigurationHash changes whenever execution behavior changes.

---

Invariant 4

Model Class is mandatory for public verifiable Endpoints.

---

Invariant 5

Provider implementation is private.

---

Invariant 6

Observable behavior determines reputation.

Declared implementation does not.
